    games: ['Pokémon (anime)'],
    description: 'A December 1997 episode of the Pokémon anime triggered photosensitive seizures in approximately 685 Japanese children, resulting in the temporary suspension of the series and new broadcast guidelines across Japanese television.',
    longDescription: 'On 16 December 1997, the Pokémon anime broadcast episode 38, "Dennō Senshi Porygon" ("Electric Soldier Porygon"), which contained a sequence of rapidly alternating red and blue flashes during a simulated computer-world explosion. The sequence lasted approximately four seconds but was sufficient to trigger photosensitive epileptic episodes in an estimated 685 viewers, 150 of whom required hospitalisation. The incident was the largest mass seizure event ever linked to a television broadcast. TV Tokyo suspended the Pokémon anime immediately; the series did not return for four months, and when it did, the format included warnings about viewing distance and instructions to watch in a lit room. Porygon, the Pokémon featured in the episode, was effectively blacklisted from future anime episodes despite being entirely blameless for the animation decision.',
